June Mummery, a Brexiteer and British businesswoman, noted that 54 percent of the UK’s fishing quota to fishing boats owned by companies in countries such as Spain and Iceland. She said that they were able to access “lucrative waters” while being “unmonitored”, and asked: “Why is [the] Government allowing this to continue?” The Merchant Shipping Act of 1988 aimed to stop foreign fishing fleets from using British waters. However, two provisions were struck down by the European Court of Justice as they conflicted with European common law. It was subsequently repealed and replaced with a 1995 act of the same name.  Follow below for live updates...